10:52.986 --> 10:59.192 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
world champions cannot strike
for better conditions
and pay, which they argue is
four times less

10:59.225 --> 11:04.731 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
than their male counterparts.
The judge said
the team is bound by a no-strike
clause in

11:04.764 --> 11:07.667 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
an earlier agreement with the
U.S. Soccer
Federation.

11:07.700 --> 11:13.206 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Still to come on the "NewsHour":
what a dismal
jobs report says about the state
of the economy;

11:13.239 --> 11:17.377 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
more than a hundred Chicago
police videos
released to the public; Mark
Shields and David

11:17.410 --> 11:24.951 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Brooks take on the week's news;
and much more.

11:24.984 --> 11:34.594 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The monthly jobs report may only
provide a
snapshot of the economy, but
that picture

11:34.627 --> 11:39.732 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in May was grim, and the photo
album of the
past three months is not such a
good look.

11:39.766 --> 11:44.971 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Just under 40,000 new jobs last
month, that's
abnormally low during this long
recovery.

11:45.004 --> 11:50.677 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But even if the numbers are off,
the last
quarter shows a slowdown, just
115,000 jobs

11:50.710 --> 11:52.545 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
a month.

11:52.579 --> 11:54.681 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Let's break this all down with
David Wessel.
He's the director of the
Brookings Institution's

11:54.714 --> 11:59.152 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Hutchins Center on Fiscal and
Monetary policy,
and a contributing correspondent
to The Wall

11:59.185 --> 12:00.954 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Street Journal.

12:00.987 --> 12:04.324 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Thirty-eight thousand jobs,
everybody's kind
of stunned by that. Some of
those had to be

12:04.357 --> 12:06.125 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the Verizon workers and the
strike.

12:06.159 --> 12:08.061 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID WESSEL, The Wall Street
Journal: Right.
It would have been twice as many
jobs if it

12:08.094 --> 12:14.534 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
hadn't been for the Verizon
strike, but, still,
that 115,000 jobs a month over
the past three

12:14.567 --> 12:16.669 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
months is much slower than we
have been seeing.

12:16.703 --> 12:19.205 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We have been seeing over 200,000
jobs a month.

12:19.238 --> 12:22.875 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And, as we
were talking
about, that the unemployment
rate decreased,

12:22.909 --> 12:24.510 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
but it was the worst kind of
decrease you
want.

12:24.544 --> 12:26.379 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DAVID WESSEL: Right.

12:26.412 --> 12:29.549 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We like it when the unemployment
rate declines
because more people find work.
We don't like

12:29.582 --> 12:33.820 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it when people drop out of the
work force.
As I said earlier, about
half-a-million people

12:33.853 --> 12:39.559 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
dropped out of the work force, a
lot of whom
were in the over age 55 group, a
lot of increase

12:39.592 --> 12:44.697 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in -- a lot of dropouts in the
high school
dropout class. So that's really
troubling.

12:44.731 --> 12:49.035 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it reverses a trend we had
been seeing
over the past few months of more
people coming

12:49.068 --> 12:50.970 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
into the job market.

12:51.004 --> 12:53.740 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So, there's a
stronger correlation
between higher education and
unemployment?

12:53.773 --> 12:55.608 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DAVID WESSEL: That's right.

12:55.642 --> 13:01.814 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So, if you're a college
graduate, the unemployment
rate is about 2.1 percent in
May, the new

13:01.848 --> 13:06.552 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
numbers out. If you're a high
school dropout,
it's half of what it was during
the recession,

13:06.586 --> 13:08.321 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
but it's still 7 percent, much
higher.

13:08.354 --> 13:11.691 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And then when
you break
it down by race, there are wild
fluctuations

13:11.724 --> 13:13.626 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
in unemployment that way?

13:13.660 --> 13:16.229 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID WESSEL: Right. As always,
about -- unemployment
for black people in America is
twice that

13:16.262 --> 13:18.097 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
for white people.

13:18.131 --> 13:22.001 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I think what's really
important is here,
is that it's not that the
economy is getting

13:22.035 --> 13:26.806 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
worse. It's just that it's
getting better
much more slowly. And that's the
disappointing

13:26.839 --> 13:30.109 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
part. We weren't ready for this
recovery to
start losing steam.

13:30.143 --> 13:33.646 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Yes. When we
talk about
those chunks of time that we're
looking at

13:33.680 --> 13:38.618 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the jobs report, quarter by
quarter, and as
slow as this has been, do we
know if this

13:38.651 --> 13:44.357 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is a bad patch or if this is a
major kind
of sea shift in how much slower
our growth

13:44.390 --> 13:45.658 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
is happening?

13:45.692 --> 13:47.894 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID WESSEL: We don't know. And
that's really
the question.

13:47.927 --> 13:52.198 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Is this a few months of bad
patch and things
will pick up later in the year,
as happened

13:52.231 --> 13:57.403 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the past couple of years?
People are saying,
the forecasters, for what it's
worth, say

13:57.437 --> 14:01.841 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that the economy should do
better in the second
quarter than the very lousy
first quarter.

14:01.874 --> 14:07.714 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But there are some worrisome
signs. Auto sales
have been weak. Businesses seem
to be squeezed

14:07.747 --> 14:12.919 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on their profits, and they're a
little uncertain
about what his happening to
policy, so they're

14:12.952 --> 14:14.721 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
not investing.

14:14.754 --> 14:18.357 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, it's really one of those
moments where
we could look back on this say
just it was

14:18.391 --> 14:21.794 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a bad patch, but we could look
back and say
this was an inflection point.

14:21.828 --> 14:25.098 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right, one
group of
people who study this report
this very closely,

14:25.131 --> 14:30.970 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the Fed, and they're meeting
soon. What does
this mean? Is this sort of
enough of an indicator

14:31.003 --> 14:32.872 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
where maybe we shouldn't make
any changes?

14:32.905 --> 14:36.876 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID WESSEL: I think that it
looks like the
Fed will not raise interest
rates on June

14:36.909 --> 14:38.678 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
15.

14:38.711 --> 14:41.514 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The markets had been expecting
them to raise
rates. After these numbers came
out today,

14:41.547 --> 14:45.585 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the market has changed its mind,
and Governor
Lael Brainard of the Federal
Reserve Board

14:45.618 --> 14:51.023 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
was pretty gloomy about what she
saw in the
numbers. So, the guessing now is
maybe they

14:51.057 --> 14:55.361 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
raise rates in July, maybe they
wait until
September, but certainly not in
June.

14:55.394 --> 14:58.865 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: There's a
sliver of a silver
lining here, which is the hourly
rates.

14:58.898 --> 15:00.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DAVID WESSEL: Right.

15:00.700 --> 15:06.339 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The only silver lining in this
otherwise dismal
report was that wages are going
up. Wages

15:06.372 --> 15:10.810 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have risen about 2.5 percent
average hourly
earnings over the past 12
months. And the

15:10.843 --> 15:14.747 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
White House was quick to point
out that, if
you just look over the first
four or five

15:14.781 --> 15:20.253 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
months of 2016, wages have been
going up at
better than a 3 percent annual
rate.

15:20.286 --> 15:24.457 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, that is encouraging and that
is important
because it means that there's --
the labor

15:24.490 --> 15:29.729 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
market is tightening and
consumers will have
money to spend, and so that's
encouraging

15:29.762 --> 15:32.098 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
sign and one I think people
weren't expecting.

15:32.131 --> 15:35.968 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And is there a
distinction
between part-time workers
looking for work,

15:36.002 --> 15:38.037 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
full-time workers looking for
work? How does
that fit in?

15:38.070 --> 15:40.006 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DAVID WESSEL: Yes.

15:40.039 --> 15:43.176 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, one of the things that has
been disturbing
about the recovery is a very,
very large fraction

15:43.209 --> 15:47.647 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of workers by historic standards
have been
working part-time, but they tell
government

15:47.680 --> 15:51.050 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
survey people, we really wish we
were looking
for a full-time job.

15:51.083 --> 15:55.421 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, that number has come down
quite a bit
since the recession, but it
still remains

15:55.454 --> 16:00.893 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
much worse than it was before
the recession.
So that's one of the worrisome
signs. We don't

16:00.927 --> 16:05.431 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
want the recovery to run out of
steam before
all those part-time workers who
want full-time

16:05.464 --> 16:07.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
jobs can get them.

16:07.200 --> 16:07.466 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right,
David Wessel
from the Brookings Institution,
thanks so

16:07.500 --> 16:08.167 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
much.

16:08.201 --> 16:13.806 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DAVID WESSEL: You're welcome.

16:13.840 --> 16:24.483 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Now: a major
release of
video exposing the police force
in Chicago.

16:24.517 --> 16:28.254 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The relationship between many
residents, the
police and the mayor has been
extremely tense

16:28.287 --> 16:33.726 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for months now, leading to
protests and suspicion,
especially after a nearly
two-year delay in

16:33.759 --> 16:36.863 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the release of a video involving
a police
shooting.

16:36.896 --> 16:41.100 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The city has traditionally
withheld these
kind of videos until
investigations were complete,

16:41.133 --> 16:45.805 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but, under pressure, the policy
has changed
and Chicago now appears to be
the largest

16:45.838 --> 16:50.877 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
American city to release videos
showing potentially
excessive force.

16:50.910 --> 16:52.245 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown has our report.

16:52.278 --> 16:55.248 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And a warning: Some of the
images in this
story may be disturbing.

16:55.281 --> 17:00.486 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: It's a stunning
release for
its sheer size and scope. Today,
Chicago's

17:00.519 --> 17:06.926 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Independent Police Review Board
released scores
of recordings related to 101
cases involving

17:06.959 --> 17:12.131 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
officer-related shootings and
other incidents
in which civilians were injured
or killed.

17:12.164 --> 17:17.336 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The videos came from dashboard
cameras and
other sources. They involve
alleged misconduct

17:17.370 --> 17:22.875 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in cases that remain under
investigation.
In one video, an unarmed man was
shot by police

17:22.909 --> 17:27.146 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
after he allegedly caused a
disturbance on
a bus and struck a driver.

17:27.179 --> 17:31.684 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Another, shot on a cell phone,
shows police
hitting someone after arriving
at a scene

17:31.717 --> 17:33.920 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
where there was open alcohol.

17:33.953 --> 17:38.758 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Today, Sharon Fairley, chief
administrator
of the review authority, said
the release

17:38.791 --> 17:41.494 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is part of an effort to make the
department
more open.

17:41.527 --> 17:43.496 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
SHARON FAIRLEY, Chicago
Independent Police
Review Authority: These past few
months, as

17:43.529 --> 17:50.369 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the city has struggled with so
many questions
about policing and about police
accountability,

17:50.403 --> 17:56.375 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it has been clear that we all
agree that there's
a lack of trust and that
increased transparency

17:56.409 --> 17:58.844 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is essential to rebuilding that
trust.

17:58.878 --> 18:02.581 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Fairley added,
though, that
the videos only show so much.

18:02.615 --> 18:07.720 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SHARON FAIRLEY: It's really
important for
you to keep in mind that these
materials may

18:07.753 --> 18:13.626 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
not convey all of the facts and
considerations
that are relevant to an
investigation of an

18:13.659 --> 18:15.594 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
officer's conduct.

18:15.628 --> 18:19.498 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: For its part, the
police union
called today's release of the
videos irresponsible.

18:19.532 --> 18:25.104 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Anger and frustration with the
police department
came to a head last year after a
video was

18:25.137 --> 18:30.609 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
released showing a white officer
killing black
teenager Laquan McDonald. The
event occurred

18:30.643 --> 18:32.478 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
in 2014.

18:32.511 --> 18:37.283 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Facing a firestorm, Mayor Rahm
Emanuel sacked
the police superintendent,
replacing him with

18:37.316 --> 18:40.252 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a new chief, veteran Eddie
Johnson.

18:40.286 --> 18:45.191 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And let's go to Chicago for
reactions to these
videos from Lori Lightfoot,
former chair of

18:45.224 --> 18:49.528 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the city's Police Accountability
Task Force.
It was formed by the mayor after
criticism

18:49.562 --> 18:54.233 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the department and his
office. She's now
president of the Chicago Police
Board, an

18:54.266 --> 18:56.936 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
independent civilian group
appointed by the
mayor.

18:56.969 --> 18:58.871 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And welcome to you.

18:58.904 --> 19:03.642 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Your task force had called for
this kind of
thing, the release of videos.
Why was it important

19:03.676 --> 19:05.745 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and why has it finally happened?

19:05.778 --> 19:10.249 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LORI LIGHTFOOT, President,
Chicago Police
Board: Well, it's important
because this information

19:10.282 --> 19:13.986 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
from these incidents is
something that people
in the community care a lot
about.

19:14.020 --> 19:18.024 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They want to know what happened.
They want
to know what specific actions
police officers

19:18.057 --> 19:22.795 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have taken, and whether or not
those actions
are consistent with law, ethics
and respectful

19:22.828 --> 19:25.097 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of community engagement.

19:25.131 --> 19:30.302 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So moving this process forward
to this point
with the release of video, audio
and also

19:30.336 --> 19:36.208 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
police reports is a very, very
important step
towards accountability and
really restoring

19:36.242 --> 19:40.246 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
legitimacy of the police
department in a lot
of communities across Chicago.

19:40.279 --> 19:44.083 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Is it possible to
say yet what
we have learned today from these
recordings,

19:44.116 --> 19:48.687 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
either in terms of individual
cases or some
larger patterns or themes?

19:48.721 --> 19:51.891 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LORI LIGHTFOOT: I think it's too
soon to tell
that.

19:51.924 --> 19:58.130 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As the lead-in said, this is 101
cases. It's
a significant volume of data,
but I know people

19:58.164 --> 20:01.734 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are going to be spending time
going through
that, and I think we will learn
more about

20:01.767 --> 20:07.373 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it in the coming days. But I
think we should
focused on and emphasize the
point that Chicago

20:07.406 --> 20:11.977 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
now becomes a leader in
transparency and putting
this kind of information out.

20:12.011 --> 20:14.880 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It is a very big and important
moment in our
history.

20:14.914 --> 20:19.985 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: We heard -- you
heard Sharon
Fairley talk about the
limitations of these

20:20.019 --> 20:25.124 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
videos, in terms of how -- in
some cases how
much or how little it shows us.
Do you agree

20:25.157 --> 20:27.660 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
with that, that we should be
careful in watching
them?

20:27.693 --> 20:32.298 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LORI LIGHTFOOT: I do agree with
that, because
the videos by definition are
going to capture

20:32.331 --> 20:36.602 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a particular snapshot in time
from a particular
perspective. They're not going
to tell the

20:36.635 --> 20:38.471 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
entire story.

20:38.504 --> 20:42.441 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, many times, those videos
and the audio
will be meaningful and giving
the public an

20:42.475 --> 20:47.680 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
understanding of what has
happened when. But
Sharon, I think, is 100 percent
right that

